<h2>Solar Incentives in Durham</h2>
<p>Durham residents have access to several attractive solar incentives that significantly reduce the upfront cost of installation. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit on the total system cost, including equipment and installation, which remains at this rate through 2032 before stepping down to 26% in 2033. North Carolina offers additional state-level incentives, including property tax exemptions for the added value of solar installations and sales tax exemptions on solar equipment purchases. Duke Energy provides net metering programs allowing customers to receive retail rate credits for excess solar energy fed back into the grid, though they've recently implemented time-of-use rates that can affect net metering benefits. Additionally, North Carolina participates in renewable energy certificate (REC) programs, though these markets have become less lucrative in recent years. Durham County and the state also offer various financing programs and low-interest loans through organizations like the North Carolina Sustainable Energy Association to make solar more accessible to homeowners.</p>

